<hr><p>
NEW!  Check out the Computational Geometry Impact Task Force's report, 
<!WA8><a href="http://graphics.lcs.mit.edu/~seth/pubs/taskforce/techrep.html">
"Application Challenges to Computational Geometry"</a>, also as
<!WA9><a href="http://graphics.lcs.mit.edu/~seth/pubs/taskforce.ps"> postscript</a> and
<!WA10><a href="http://graphics.lcs.mit.edu/~seth/pubs/taskforce.ps.Z"> compressed postscript</a>, and
<!WA11><a href="http://graphics.lcs.mit.edu/~seth/pubs/taskforce.dvi"> dvi</a>
(or, anon ftp to graphics.lcs.mit.edu, then cd pub, get taskforce.ps.Z).

<p> From 1993-94, I was a postdoc in computer graphics and
computational geometry at Princeton, working with Pat Hanrahan,
Michael Cohen, David Dobkin, and Bernard Chazelle.  The year before
that, I postdoc'ed at the Hebrew University Givat Ram campus in
Jerusalem.  From 1987-92, I was at UC Berkeley, completing a
dissertation with <!WA12><a href="http://http.cs.Berkeley.edu/~sequin/"> Carlo Sequin</a>.

<p> My research interests include global illumination algorithms;
visibility computations; constrained spatial subdivisions; visual
simulation; interactive algorithm visualization, verification and
animation; self-checking geometric algorithms; real-time ray-traced
imagery; and machine vision, including fully automated acquisition
of geometric models and other forms of data.

<p> I head the 
<!WA13><a href="http://graphics.lcs.mit.edu/sigroup/homepage.html"> Synthetic
Imagery Group</a>, which is part of the
<!WA14><a href="http://graphics.lcs.mit.edu/"> MIT Computer Graphics Group</a>.
Our main research emphases are 
1) <!WA15><a href="http://graphics.lcs.mit.edu/~seth/city/city.html"> digitizing whole cities</a> with pose-instrumented
(6-DOF) digital cameras; 2) managing and rendering <!WA16><a href="http://graphics.lcs.mit.edu/~seth/complexity.html">     
extremely complex geometric datasets</a>; 3) generating <!WA17><a href="http://graphics.lcs.mit.edu/~seth/raytracedimagery.html">
real-time ray-traced imagery</a> on general-purpose (i.e., non-graphics) 
hardware; and 4) techniques for remote, interactive, collaborative
<!WA18><a href="http://graphics.lcs.mit.edu/~bwporter/EduFuse/"> undergraduate education</a>.
<p>
Also, <!WA19><a href="http://graphics.lcs.mit.edu/~dorsey"> Julie Dorsey</a> has
recently joined the <!WA20><a href="http://alberti.mit.edu/arch/arch.html">
Dept. of Architecture</a> and 
<!WA21><a href="http://www.lcs.mit.edu/"> Lab for Computer Science</a>
at MIT, and is building the 
<!WA22><a href="http://graphics.lcs.mit.edu/visual_simulation/">
Visual Simulation Group</a>.

<p> This semester (Fall 1996), I'm teaching <!WA23><a
href="http://graphics.lcs.mit.edu/6.837/f96/"> 6.837 (Introduction to
Computer Graphics)</a>, which will meet TR from 230-4pm in MIT
building/room <!WA24><a href="http://registrar.mit.edu/map/mitmap.cgi?3-270">
3-270</a>.

<p>
Spring 1996, I taught <!WA25><a href="http://graphics.lcs.mit.edu/~seth/6.046-S96/6.046.html"> 6.046 (Introduction
